.\" Manpage for ntlmv1scan.
.TH NTLMV1SCAN 8 "April 2026" "ntlmv1scan 1.0" "ntlmv1scan Manual"
.SH NAME
ntlmv1scan \- detect NTLMv1 authentication traffic on Linux systems
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ntlmv1scan
\-i
.IR interface | all
[\-c
.IR packet_count ]
.br
.B ntlmv1scan
\-h
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ntlmv1scan
captures raw Ethernet frames from a live network interface (or from all
available interfaces when
.B all
is specified) using a Linux AF_PACKET raw socket, filters TCP traffic on SMB
ports 139 and 445, and flags NTLMSSP AUTHENTICATE (Type 3) messages whose LM
and NT response lengths are both 24 bytes.
When a hit is found, it performs a best-effort lookup of the local process
(PID/command) owning the matching TCP socket.
.PP
Root privileges (or
.BR CAP_NET_RAW )
are required to open a raw socket.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-i
.IR interface | all
Network interface to capture from (for example
.BR eth0 ),
or
.B all
to capture from all available network interfaces simultaneously.
This option is required.
.TP
.B \-c
.IR packet_count
Stop after
.I packet_count
total packets have been received.
Default is 0 (unlimited).
.TP
.B \-h
Print usage and exit.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Scan completed and no NTLMv1 traffic was detected.
.TP
.B 1
At least one potential NTLMv1 authentication was detected.
Non-zero is also returned on fatal errors.
.SH EXAMPLES
Scan the
.B eth0
interface indefinitely:
.IP
.B # ntlmv1scan -i eth0
.PP
Scan the first 10000 captured packets on
.BR ens3 :
.IP
.B # ntlmv1scan -i ens3 -c 10000
.PP
Scan all available interfaces indefinitely:
.IP
.B # ntlmv1scan -i all
.SH NOTES
The tool inspects only Ethernet frames carrying IPv4 TCP segments.
Tunnelled, encapsulated, or VLAN-tagged traffic is not decoded.
.SH AUTHOR
Gratien Dhaese and contributors
